{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586759"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15096"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15096"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0,0.19,0.19,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64574"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"3823"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8129"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64574"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a two week history of intermittent blood in his urine. He has no other current urinary symptoms, but did have a urinary tract infection two months ago. His medical history includes lymphoma treated with cyclophosphamide 10 years ago. He is a non-smoker, drinks about eight glasses of wine at weekends and has four cups of coffee a day. He works as a builder. The physical examination is unremarkable. Urinalysis confirms the present of blood in the urine and a cystoscopy identifies a transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely risk factor for the development of this cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cyclophosphamide exposure","Excessive caffeine intake","High alcohol consumption","Occupational paint exposure","Recurrent urinary tract infections"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclophosphamide\u003C/strong\u003E is a chemotherapeutic agent that increases bladder cancer risk through its toxic metabolite acrolein. This metabolite causes chronic inflammation and DNA damage to the bladder epithelium. Patients require adequate hydration and sometimes mesna (a uroprotective agent) during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcessive caffeine intake\u003C/strong\u003E may increase urinary frequency, it is not associated with bladder cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EOccupational paint exposure\u003C/strong\u003E can increase risk, but is less significant than cyclophosphamide. \u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent urinary tract infections\u003C/strong\u003E may cause chronic inflammation but have a weaker association with bladder cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors include smoking, advanced age, male gender, and exposure to aromatic amines in industrial chemicals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder cancer commonly presents with painless haematuria","Cyclophosphamide exposure increases bladder cancer risk through toxic metabolite acrolein","Intravesical Bacillus Calmette-Gu\u00e9rin (BCG) immunotherapy is effective for high-risk non-muscle invasive bladder cancer"],"references":["Jankovi\u0107 S, Radosavljevi\u0107 V. Risk factors for bladder cancer. Tumori. 2007 Jan-Feb;93(1):4-12. doi: 10.1177/030089160709300102. PMID: 17455864.","Cumberbatch MGK, Jubber I, Black PC, Esperto F, Figueroa JD, Kamat AM, Kiemeney L, Lotan Y, Pang K, Silverman DT, Znaor A, Catto JWF. Epidemiology of Bladder Cancer: A Systematic Review and Contemporary Update of Risk Factors in 2018. Eur Urol. 2018 Dec;74(6):784-795. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2018.09.001. Epub 2018 Sep 26. PMID: 30268659.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15096"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T09:41:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T09:42:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64574"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description"